unit.name: 1 SS Panzer Division "LAH"
unit.History: The history of the division starts with the "Stabswache Berlin", a unit formed by Sepp Dietrich in 1933 to serve as Adolf Hitler's personal guard. It was later renamed "Leibstandarte Adolf Hitler" and expanded to a motorized regiment which took part in the campaigns in Poland and the West. Formed into a brigade, the unit served on the Balkans and on the southern sector of the Eastern Front. In 1942 it was transferred to France, and was upgraded once again, to become a Panzergrenadier Division. Sent back to the Eastern Front early in 1943, it fought at Kharkov and Kursk, before being sent to Italy. Renamed a Panzerdivision, it was again committed on the Eastern Front, where it suffered heavy losses. In June 6 1944 the division was resting and refitting in Belgium, and later that month in was sent to Normandy, where it again suffered heavily. During the Autumn of 1944 it was more or less brought back up to strength, although its Panzer Regiment had only one battalion instead of two. This was remedied by the incorporation of the SS schwere Panzer Abt. 501 (with King Tigers) into the division. For Operation "Wacht am Rhein" the division formed four Kampfgruppen, based on the 1. SS Pz Regt, the 1. SS Pz Gr Regt, the 2. SS PzGr Regt and the SS AufklÃ¤rungs Abt.1 respectively.

commander.Name: Wilhelm Mohnke
commander.PersBio: Mohnke joined the SS in the early thirties. He commanded the II Bn of the Leibstandarte during the campaign in the West and on the Balkans, where he was wounded and lost a foot. After his recuperation, Mohnke spend some time in the replacement battalion of the Leibstandarte, before taking over the 26. Pz Gr Regt of the 12. SS Panzerdivision "Hitlerjugend". He led this regiment during the campaign in Normandy, and was awarded the Knight's Cross. On August 31, 1944 he took command of the Leibstandarte after its previous commander, Theodor Wisch, was wounded.

unit.name: 1 SS PZ Rgt HQ
unit.History: Kampfgruppe Peiper was formed to spearhead the attack of the 1st SS Pz Div "Leibstandarte Adolf Hitler" in the Ardennes. Its staff was the staff of SS Pz Regt 1, and it consisted of a Panzer battalion, a heavy Panzer battalion (King Tigers), a mechanized Panzer Grenadier battalion and various Flak, Artillery and Engineer units. Peiper's force was 'tank heavy', and its armour had difficulty moving across the rugged Ardennes terrain. Still, Kampgruppe Peiper advanced further west than any other unit of the 6th Pz Army.

commander.Name: Jochen Peiper
commander.PersBio: Born in 1915, Peiper volunteered for the SS in 1935. At the start of the war, he commanded the 11th Coy of the Leibstandarte, then a regiment. He fought in France, the Balkans and Russia. In 1942 he became commander of the III (gep) Bn of SS Pz Gr Regt 2. From December 1943 he commanded SS Pz Regt 1. Although he was successful leading his troops and highly decorated, Peiper became notorious for the atrocities committed by units under his command, both against civilians in Italy and against American POWs in the Ardennes.
